\section{Introduction}
This project investigates whether the introduction of Norway’s public smoking ban led to a reduction in \textbf{regular smoking prevalence} among the population. Using an econometric Difference-in-Differences (DiD) framework, we aim to identify the causal effect of the smoking ban (implemented in \textbf{June 2004}) on smoking behavior by comparing trends in Norway (Treatment Group) and Spain (Control Group) before and after the policy.

\section{Research Question}
\begin{quote}
\emph{Did the 2004 smoking place ban in Norway cause a reduction in the country's regular smokers' percentage relative to Spain?}
\end{quote}
This question shifts the focus from health outcomes to the \textbf{behavioral mechanism} by which such a policy operates.

\section{Data Description}
The analysis uses annual data from Norway (Treated) and Spain (Control) covering the period from \textbf{1978 to 2020}, with a focus on the pre- and post-ban periods around 2004. The data processing steps were as follows:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Data Cleaning and Merging:} Raw data on smoking prevalence for Norway and Spain were loaded and cleaned. For Norway, data was read from Excel and columns were renamed and filtered. For Spain, data was provided as a dictionary and converted to a DataFrame.
    \item \textbf{Interpolation:} Both countries had missing years in their annual smoking prevalence series. We created a complete range of years and used linear interpolation to fill in missing values, ensuring a balanced panel for analysis. Tobacco price indices for both countries were also processed from monthly data, extracting January values for each year and interpolating as needed.
    \item \textbf{Panel Construction:} The data was reshaped to long format, resulting in one row per country-year with columns for year, country, smoking prevalence, and tobacco price. Additional variables were created: a Norway dummy, a post-2004 dummy, and a treatment interaction term for DiD analysis.
\end{itemize}

