\subsection{Conceptual Framework}
The DiD strategy compares the change in smoking prevalence in Norway before and after 2004 with the corresponding change in Spain over the same period. This calculation removes the effects of general European trends and pre-existing country differences.

\section{Econometric Specification}
The main estimating equation is:
\begin{equation}
Y_{it} = \alpha + \beta_1 \text{Post}_t + \beta_2 \text{Norway}_i + \delta (\text{Post}_t \times \text{Norway}_i) + \gamma_1 \text{TobaccoPrice}_{it} + \varepsilon_{it}
\end{equation}
where:
\begin{itemize}
    \item $Y_{it}$ is the annual smokers' percentage in country $i$ at time $t$.
    \item $\text{Post}_t$ is the dummy variable equal to 1 for years $\ge 2004$ (treatment period).
    \item $\text{Norway}_i$ is the country dummy variable (1 for Norway, 0 for Spain).
    \item $\delta$ is the DiD estimator of interest, capturing the causal impact of the smoking ban.
    \item $\text{TobaccoPrice}_{it}$ is the country-year specific control variable for tobacco price.
    \item $\varepsilon_{it}$ is the error term.
\end{itemize}
The coefficient $\delta$ measures the average treatment effect of the smoking ban on the smokers' percentage in Norway relative to Spain, conditional on parallel trends and the control for price effects.
